<h2>Schema Markup</h2>
<p><a href="/blog/schema-markup-seo-guide/">Schema markup</a> affects how your site appears in search results. Both plugins generate structured data, but their approaches differ.</p>
<h3>Rank Math Schema</h3>
<p>Rank Math offers 16+ schema types in the free version. Pro adds 20+ types with an advanced schema builder. You can create custom schema, use schema templates for recurring patterns, and even import schema from other websites.</p>
<p>Free schema types include: Article, Product, Review, Recipe, FAQ, HowTo, Course, Event, Local Business, Video, Book, Person, Job Posting, Movie, Music, and Software Application.</p>
<p>The advanced schema builder (Pro) lets you create any custom JSON-LD markup without writing code.</p>
<h3>Yoast Schema</h3>
<p>Yoast takes a different approach. Instead of offering many individual schema types, Yoast builds a Schema Graph. This connects Person, Organization, WebPage, and Article entities into an interconnected model.</p>
<p>The Schema Graph approach is technically rigorous and aligns well with Google's <a href="/blog/eeat-google-quality-guide/">E-E-A-T</a> signals. But the free version is limited to basic Article, FAQ (via Gutenberg blocks), and HowTo schema. Product schema requires the $178.80/year WooCommerce bundle.</p>
<h3>Schema Verdict</h3>
<p>Rank Math wins on quantity and accessibility. Yoast wins on architectural rigor. For most WordPress sites, Rank Math's 16 free schema types cover every common use case. Enterprise sites that need entity-level schema sophistication may prefer Yoast's Graph model.</p>
