<h2>AI Features</h2>
<p>Both plugins have added AI capabilities. Their approaches are different.</p>
<h3>Rank Math Content AI</h3>
<p>Rank Math offers a separate Content AI subscription at $47.88/year for 60,000 credits. It includes 40+ AI writing tools, 125+ prompt templates, and a RankBot assistant for research and content questions.</p>
<p>The catch: Content AI credits are not included with plugin plans. You get a 15-day trial with Pro/Business/Agency plans. After that, AI features stop unless you buy a separate Content AI subscription. Credits cost 1 per word generated and 500 per keyword research query. Credits do not roll over.</p>
<h3>Yoast AI Features</h3>
<p>Yoast Premium includes AI Generate (creates 5 title and meta description options per click) and AI Optimize (automatically improves keyphrase placement in your content). No separate credit system. No per-word charges.</p>
<p>The AI+ Package ($358.80/year) adds AI Brand Insights. This unique feature tracks how your brand appears in answers from ChatGPT, Gemini, and Perplexity. No other WordPress SEO plugin offers this.</p>
<p>Yoast also provides a Google Docs add-on that lets you optimize content directly in Google Docs before publishing to WordPress.</p>
<h3>AI Verdict</h3>
<p>Rank Math offers broader AI content creation tools. Yoast offers tighter integration with no credit headaches. If you want AI writing assistance inside WordPress, Rank Math Content AI gives you more options. If you want AI metadata optimization without managing credits, Yoast is simpler.</p>
<p>The AI Brand Insights feature in Yoast AI+ is unique and worth considering if <a href="/blog/track-ai-search-visibility/">AI search visibility</a> matters to your business.</p>
<h2>Readability Analysis</h2>
<p>This is Yoast's strongest advantage. And most comparison articles understate how large the gap is.</p>
<h3>Yoast Readability</h3>
<p>Yoast checks your content for:</p>
<ul>
<li>Flesch-Kincaid Reading Ease score</li>
<li>Passive voice percentage</li>
<li>Sentence length distribution</li>
<li>Paragraph length</li>
<li>Transition word usage</li>
<li>Subheading distribution</li>
<li>Consecutive sentence variety</li>
<li>Inclusive language (age, gender, disability, socioeconomic status)</li>
</ul>
<p>These checks work in 25+ languages. For content teams with non-SEO writers, this is the single most useful feature either plugin offers. It teaches writers to produce <a href="/blog/seo-content-writing/">SEO-friendly content</a> without needing SEO training.</p>
<h3>Rank Math Readability</h3>
<p>Rank Math folds a basic readability score into its overall SEO score. It does not offer Flesch scoring, passive voice detection, transition word analysis, or inclusive language checks.</p>
<h3>Readability Verdict</h3>
<p>Yoast wins by a wide margin. If your team relies on content readability coaching, Yoast is the better choice. If you handle readability yourself or use external editing tools, this feature gap does not matter.</p>
